From: alcuin <alcuin@erols.com>
Source: South China Morning Post, Wed 6 Jan 1999 [edited
http://www.scmp.com/news/

Harbin flu may spread to SAR
-------------------------------------
The flu virus sweeping northern China could spread to Hong Kong in
the peak influenza season around the Lunar New Year, a mainland
health expert has warned.
The new A strain of Harbin virus H3N2, which hit Harbin city in
November, spread to Shenyang, Beijing and Tianjin in a month and is
now affecting Wuhan and Shanghai.
Experts warned that if the virus continued to spread south it could
hit the SAR [Hong Kong next month around the Lunar New Year. The
holiday is traditionally a peak time for flu.
More than 70 per cent of the population in Harbin city in
Heilongjiang province has [sic flu.
Mainland hospitals are reporting huge increases in the number of flu
patients seeking remedies each day, while some schools have been
forced to cancel classes.
Hong Kong health officials said they were monitoring the situation
closely but there was no need to panic.
[Hong Kong Health Department statistics show that more than 2800
cases of type A H3N2 flu were reported during the peak season last
February and March.
--
Byline: Rhonda Lam Wan
